I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API endpoint as the first step in our workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic JSON schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "tool": {"type": "string"},
      "timestamp": {"type": "string"},
      "execution_context": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "step": {"type": "number"},
          "total_tools_executed": {"type": "number"}
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["status", "tool", "timestamp"]
  },
  "data": {
    "status": "completed",
    "tool": "network_fetcher",
    "timestamp": "2025-08-28T12:05:22.244276",
    "execution_context": {
      "step": 0,
      "total_tools_executed": 0
    }
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            The validation was successful. Now I'll proceed with the final step of parsing the data into a structured format using the data_processing_parser tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/output.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json",
    "structure": {
      "status": "string",
      "tool": "string",
      "timestamp": "datetime",
      "execution_context": {
        "step": "number",
        "total_tools_executed": "number"
      }
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll attempt to read cached data using the file_operations_reader tool as an alternative to the failed network fetch.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
